<p>Copy and paste this into a .txt file for a Llama 3.2 summarization test. Let me know if you want a different genre, length, or another text. A small fire started in dead underbrush because a hiker left a cigarette. The children had worked hard, so the healthy trees resisted the flames. The fire found no easy path. Rangers arrived quickly and stopped it before it spread. The feeling said, “Danger, fire.” After that season, when the wind blew through the redwoods, villagers said they could almost hear the trees singing. In a shadow of an ancient redwood forest lived a girl named Mira. She could feel trees speak, not with words, but with slow, deep feelings that came through her bare feet on mossy paths. Later, Mira sat with Grandfather Cedar. The feeling was gratitude, warm and slow like sunlight through leaves. Mira returned to Grandfather Cedar. The feeling grew stronger and sharper. She sat beneath him for three days, listening. On the fourth day she understood: the danger was not a wildfire from outside, but rot from within. A sickness spread through roots, carried by tiny beetles. She gathered the village children. Together they collected sap from healthy trees, mixed it with herbs the elders knew, and painted the mixture on the trunks nearest Grandfather Cedar. It was a desperate, hopeful gesture. She leaned against him and whispered, “We heard you.” She ran to the ranger station. “The forest is afraid,” she told them. “There’s going to be a fire.” The forest answered in the rustle of a thousand branches, a sound like breathing, like thanks. The oldest tree, Grandfather Cedar, was over a thousand years old. His voice was the slowest of all, a low vibration that took days to form a single thought. One spring, Mira pressed her palm to his rough bark and felt something urgent. The rangers smiled kindly but explained there had been no lightning, no campfires left burning. “The season is wet,” they said. “Everything is safe.” Weeks passed. Summer came hot and dry. One morning Mira woke to smoke—not thick, not raging, but thin and acrid. She ran to the forest.</p>